@susmech "How would Komodo describe current state of blockchain"

Good question, we wrote an entire blog post about it some time ago: https://komodoplatform.com/the-promise-challenges-and-evolution-of-the-blockchain-industry/

As a summary, I think most projects are "technology followers" who take what the industry currently perceives as the best technology. They cut and pase an incrementally better solution together as their solution rather than look at the fundamentals and come up with new innovations that could revolutionize the industry.

@acidbird aws has hundreds of tech partners in different industries.
the aws partner network is tiered, and at different levels the partners work together to form new industry solutions.
blockchain tech is a new industry, and komodo is an innovator - so that's where we want to be, creating new industry solutions.

@acidbird hiring process is HR related.   i'm not in HR, however this is how i've seen komodo work with new hires:
 - we will always be ready to collaborate with talented devs with enthusiasm, drive & an exceptional history.   we cannot turn back great devs.   some devs and other techs have approached, and then find their own niche - sometimes it's in kmd, sometimes it's in a related project.  there are dozens of related projects with finite timelines.   and then these devs/techs move onto some other project.   then they drop in & out to fill some technology requirement.
 - when an advert is posted, there is a need to fill a gap for a longer term & hone the skills of the new hire to specific tech or specific new tech usually.   there is a focus on not creating technical debt.  technical debt is not a sustainable way to run a project like kmd, from a HR perspective.
